      "For any `S тИИ ЁЭУЭ[тЙа] 0`, it contains a set of the form `(-╬╡, ╬╡) \\ {0}` for some `╬╡ > 0`.\n- Then, for any `k > 1/╬╡`, we have `0 < 1/k < ╬╡`, so `1/k тИИ (-╬╡, ╬╡) \\ {0} тКЖ S`.\n\nBut perhaps Lean knows this already.\n\nBut maybe we can proceed as follows:\n1. We have `Tendsto (fun x => sinh(r x)/x) (ЁЭУЭ[тЙа] 0) (ЁЭУЭ r)`. \n2. We have `Tendsto (fun k => 1/k) atTop (ЁЭУЭ 0)`.\n3. And `1/k тЙа 0` for `k > 0`.\n\nThen, perhaps we can use `Filter.Tendsto.mono_left` and `Filter.Tendsto.mono_right` to adjust the filters properly.\nAlternatively, perhaps we can use that if `Tendsto f l l'` and `Tendsto g l'' l` and `f` is continuous on the image of `g`, then `Tendsto (f тИШ g) l'' l'`.\nBut perhaps easier: since eventually `1/k тЙа 0`, we can use that `(fun x => sinh(r x)/x)` coincides with `(fun x => sinh(r x)/x)` on the set `{x | x тЙа 0}` which is in the filter `ЁЭУЭ[тЙа] 0`.\n\nBut perhaps instead we should use:\n1. The map `x тЖж sinh(r x)/x` is continuous at every `x тЙа 0`.\n2. Therefore, if we approach `x тЖТ 0` with `x тЙа 0`, then we have that `x = 1/k`, `k тЖТ +тИЮ`, that `sinh(r x)/x` tends to `r`.\n\nBut perhaps we can do something more like:\n1. `Tendsto (fun x",
